00:16:35.159 --> 00:16:45.159
So there, as it's referencing R Markdown, I will like there is several caching understanding in Quarto. As you are

00:16:45.679 --> 00:16:54.080
referencing R Markdown, I will say that we have the cache option for the computation. So you have a caching for the

00:16:54.080 --> 00:17:02.440
computation with the cache option. And this can be set for Jupyter engine and Nitar engine. But in each of the computation

00:17:02.440 --> 00:17:12.520
world, they will use, it will not, it's not a new caching mechanism. So if you use this caching for a document using Nitar, it

00:17:12.520 --> 00:17:20.040
will be the same caching that in R Markdown. No difference. So it will be as granular as in R Markdown, because it will be

00:17:20.040 --> 00:17:28.119
Nitar doing the caching and it works exactly the same. If you are working in a Jupyter document, engine document, it will

00:17:28.119 --> 00:17:35.160
use a caching that Jupyter provides. The same. So it could be different from like the Nitar one. So I don't know exactly the

00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:44.920
granularity if it is the same. But the caching is, will run the computation and use a caching mechanism. But in Quarto, you

00:17:44.920 --> 00:17:53.319
have also something that we call freeze. So the freezing mechanism, which is a way to tell your Quarto project to not run

00:17:53.319 --> 00:17:59.479
computation in certain condition. So it's a bit different than caching because at this point, no computation will be run. It

00:17:59.479 --> 00:18:08.839
means like if you freeze a website, you don't even need after that R or Python to render your website, your output. So I

00:18:08.839 --> 00:18:18.199
will put a link so that it will be shared. So I won't explain this in detail here. But this can be useful in some

00:18:18.199 --> 00:18:27.839
situation. And so this one is not granular at all. It's really global for the project, the Quarto project.

